Uncomfortable Questionsð

1. If you live exactly the way you lived over the last 2 weeks, for the rest of your life, where would you end up? Would you carry regrets?

2. Is there an unexpressed part within you or an unexplored endeavour outside of you that you are surpressing because of the opinion of others? What will be the regret in 30 years time? Is that worth it?

3. If you would die tomorrow, is there anything you would regret not saying? Who is the person you would have wanted to say this to? When will you say it?

4. What is truly important to you regarding the limited time you have on this planet? Are you living, prioritizing this core value?

5. How many times did you see your parents over the last 30 days? How long do they probably have left to live? How many times will you be with them before its over? How can you make these moments count?

6. Is there anything you are not doing out of the fear of failiure? Be honest.

7. Who are you? You can not use a name, a role or a status. Use your values.

Make sure to save this post, so that you can revisit them at a later moment. 

Knowing yourself is the beginning of all wisdom. Self-reflection can be a very useful tool for this. It can be painful or confronting at times, but it can also be an anchor in the chaos we call: life. 

I hope that these questions will provide you with a little bit more insight into your current life, behaviors & values. 

Feel free to share your findings in the comments or send me a message. Send it to a friend, so that you can both live a fulfilled life.

My journey speaks to a common struggle, one where the past casts long shadows over the present, and understanding comes much later than we wish. If I had grasped back then what I now hold as truth, I'm certain the path behind me would look different. The challenge wasn't just in failing to recognize my own trauma; it was in realizing its impact years after the fact, long after it had shaped my world in ways I couldn't comprehend at the time.

Relationships, especially those rooted in genuine connection and love, can be profoundly complicated. They require us to be open in ways we've never been, to share vulnerabilities we've long kept hidden. My own story was no exception. I was dragging the weight of unresolved trauma from my childhood, mistaking it for flaws within my relationships. This baggage blurred my vision, preventing me from seeing the love and support that was right in front of me. When faced with genuine care during my most vulnerable moments, I recoiled, unable to accept it fully. This wasn't a reflection of the love offered to me but a consequence of never having experienced such support during my earlier vulnerabilities.

However, through reflection, understanding, and a steadfast commitment to personal growth, I've begun to navigate the murky waters of my past. I've become acutely aware of how these early traumas influenced me, and I'm learning how to differentiate between them and the reality of my current experiences. This journey of self-discovery has not been easy, but it has been enlightening.

Now, armed with this newfound awareness, I am dedicated to making amends. I strive to not only heal the wounds of my past but also to ensure that I do not repeat the same mistakes. My path forward is one of continued growth, understanding, and an unyielding commitment to becoming a better person. It's a testament to the power of introspection, the importance of acknowledging our past, and the transformative potential of love and support. My story, though uniquely mine, echoes a universal truth: healing begins with recognizing our struggles and believing in our capacity to overcome them.

25 Fundamental Questions for Girls & Women

Take a moment to step back, reflect on your thoughts, and navigate your journey with these questions.

Save this post for monthly self-discovery

1. What does your ideal day look like?

2. What did you want to be when you were younger?

3. Who are you most inspired by? Why?

4. Who would you love to meet? What would you ask?

5. What habit would you most like to break? What habit would you most like to start?

6. Think of a person you truly admire. What qualities do you like about that person?

7. How do you like to relax?

8. When was the last time you did something you were afraid of?

9. What are you most proud of?

10. What are you most afraid of?

11. If life stopped today, what would you regret not doing?

12. Who would you like to connect (or reconnect) with? Why?

13. What qualities do you admire in others?

14. What practical skills do you wish you had?

15. Imagine you're in your 90s. What memories would you like to have? What stories do you want to tell?

16. What is your favorite book/movie/song? Why?

17. If you could make one change in the world, what would it be?

18. What do you love to do for, or give to others?

19. What excites you?

20. What do you wish you did more of?

21. Pretend money is no object. What would you do?

22. What area of your life, right now, makes you feel the best? Why?

23. Let's jump forward a year. What would you like to have achieved in the past year?

24. What piece of advice would you give to five year old you?

25. How do you want to be remembered in life?

Men in love are the prettiest humans

The way they hold your hands in crowded streets.
The way they remember your favourite food.
The way they see your favourite movie and tell it's their favourite too.
The way they keep your handkerchief when you forget it.
The way they remember your favourite colour and wears the same colour
The way they learn to cook your favourite food.
The way they find the perfect jhumka for you.
The way they remember your periods and send chocolates.
The way they talk to us with heavy sleep eyes on face time.
The way they let us play with their hair.
The way they read your favourite book so that they can talk about it.
The way they wear our hair tie on their hand.
The way they run to open the door for us.
The way they write long good morning paragraphs for us.
The way they offer their favourite hoodie to us.
The way they play our favourite 90s songs on a long drive 
The way they buy flowers for us.
The way they look at us.

I swear,
Men in love are the prettiest humansð¤§

~Astha Mehta

Baby capybaras, known as pups, are born fully developed with eyes open and covered in fur. They are incredibly social animals and typically stay close to their mothers, nursing for the first few months of life. Capybara pups are highly precocial, meaning they can walk and even swim shortly after birth, allowing them to quickly join their family group in exploring their surroundings. Fun fact: Capybara pups are often cared for not only by their mothers but also by other females in the group, creating a communal approach to parenting within capybara communities.

â¬ï¸ Living with bipolar and how co-regulation has changed my life.

Follow us ð @a_dingles_story  for what itâs like living with bipolar, and ways I manage to stay in control while travelling full time ð

So what does it mean to co regulate? Itâs so important for every relationship not just people with mental health disorders. Co-regulating in a relationship feels like having a safe haven through the worst of emotions. Imagine this scenario: You start getting overwhelmed and burst into tears, Your partner notices this and gently reaches out, holds you and gives you the space to vent about what is going on while you experience it. They validate your feelings and help you navigate through the confusion. In that moment, you feel understood, supported, and a sense of calm washes over you. Itâs like having an emotional anchor by your side, helping you find stability and peace. I normally say I need a change of scenery when I get overwhelmed and start panicking. There have been many times I have stood in the rain and Toz has come next to me, held me, listened to me.. sometimes just hearing his heart beat is all it takes to bring me back to my calm again.

share.share_text:
It's not a lie that it's cold and dark for at least five months of the year. It varies a little between the north and south of the country, but in general, it's tough. 

Comparing it to the mild winters growing up, it's not any more depressive. And there are some very strong upsides of living in Norway:

Norway has 5,488,984 on 385,207 square kilometers. That makes 14 inhabitants per square kilometer which in terms means that you can afford your own plot of land. Even more, if you are willing to go north and away from the cities. 

That sense of land ownership is missing for so many in this generation. At least we can go places where it isn't impossible.

Apart from land prices, this country is absolutely stunning visually. And even better, you can walk in mountain chains for days without meeting anybody. 

Nature and space are my two main arguments here, but having real seasons is also something I grew to appreciate. Instead of rainy winters, it's quite lovely to see the country transform into a white wonderland, go skiing, and have a coffee on the fire. 

I have yet to live in any place where people appreciate nature and outdoor life as much as in Norway

Miso Soup and Mushroom Katsu ð

Happy Feashting!

Miso is nutty and very slightly pungent. Kombu, is used to make the stock. I also used rehydrated Mushroom stock as well. And wakame, tastes fishy. Not a lot but it does have the taste. I grew up eating fish and also Japanese food. So I love how mild Miso soup is. It is also rich in nutrients and extremely healthy. 

Recipe 

For Miso Soup
2 tbsp shiro miso
2 tbsp dried wakame seaweed 
1-2 dried kombu sheets
1/3 cup diced tofu
8-9 dry shiitake mushroom (only the rehydration stock)

- sautÃ© a block of tofu, diced (my MIL doesnât like the raw taste. So I always sautÃ© it with a bit of salt). Take half of it out for the soup, remaining half - cook in sweet teriyaki sauce for rice topping.
- In a pan add 1.5 cups of water. Add kombu. Simmer on low heat for 12 mins. Take out the kombu sheets for future use.
- Because I always make mushroom Katsu with miso soup, I also add dried mushroom stock. 
- Add 1 cup hot water to dried shitake mushrooms. Soak for 10 mins. Add the golden stock into the pan.
- Let it come to a boil, add wakame seaweed. And add the sautÃ©ed tofu. Boil for 10 mins.
- in a cup add 1/4 cup hot broth to miso paste. Mix well until no lumps are left. Turn the heat off. And add in to the broth. Mix well and cover. (Remember miso settles at the bottom. So always mix before having it)

For the Katsu 
8-9 dry Shitake musroom
1/2 cup flour divided into 2 bowl - 1/4 dry onto the drained and rehydrated mushrooms and 1/4 cup for a thick batter
Panko/breadcrumbs
Kashmiri red Chili powder
1/4 tsp salt added to the batter
Oil for deep frying

- Rehydrate the mushrooms by pouring boiling water in it. Leave it covered for 10-15 mins. The stock is healthy so add it to your rice or soups. It will not smell!
- add flour and 1/8 tsp salt on the rehydrated mushrooms
- Make the batter by mixing 1/4 cup flour, 1/4 tsp salt, 1/2 tsp Chili powder, 1/4 tsp cumin powder, and water
- adding Chili powder on panko adds a lot of taste
- dip the floured mushrooms into the batter, cover both sides.
- Then cover the mushroom with panko, generously!!
- fry in hot oil on high heat. 

Serve hot!

âThe best part of your twenties is not the financial freedom. It is not that we finally feel that we are about to make it. It isnât even found in that spectacular job offer that we worked for a full decade to obtain. The best part of your twenties is that you genuinely find your tribe. You find the people you can be completely honest with and show your entire murky self to, knowing that they will love you anyway. You find the people that, because you have been so honest, help you make yourself into the best version of you.

The best part of your twenties is the ability to be completely and authentically yourself with your girl friends. To be finally able to share with someone all of the parts of you that youâd kept hidden so long. To be able to scream with laughter while lying across a queen-sized bed, watching a movie from way back when, yet the next day be reviewing each otherâs papers, resumes, and court documents.

Itâs never the people you thought it would be that support you through the most difficult and challenging years of your life. Yet even in the surprise of it all, it makes sense. Two glasses of Argentinian Malbec into a conversation, we understand why the other feels so broken. And while we canât fix ourselves, we can absolutely work to fix the other.

The hardest part of your twenties is the friends you leave behind because they move, change themselves, or get married and find someone else to love more. There is another side. Truly, the best part of your twenties is found in the women you find in the most random places, who turn you from a broken, anxious little girl into a shining and beautiful woman.â - Claire Turner #moonloversð

I have sucked at having boundaries w/ my own brainð¤ð and now Iâm a little/lottle better  so hereâs some things that massively helped með

ð§  Mental boundaries with ourselves are essentially a how we can create ground rules or boundaries around how we invest in, care for, nourish and protect our headspaceð§ 

1) Start getting aware of when your thoughts are straying into the destructive. Observe it, donât punish yourself - just begin to notice it.

2) Begin to notice how your thoughts & feeling interact. Which comes first? How does a thought leave you feeling? Does it magnify a feeling? Do certain feelings trigger certain thoughts? 

3) Start writing out some of the thoughts you have on loop. How many of these are habitual? How long have they been there? Are they about *this* situation or do they find any excuse to sneak in?

4) Practise having a neutral reaction to some negative thoughts. Practise shrugging, acting disinterested & non-reactive.

5) Redirect your attention to something that feels good or at least not shit - can you go for a walk? Take a shower? Clean your teeth? What can you do that doesnât exasperate the feeling or further punish you for having it.

Lots to play with! Itâs the weekend, pls give yourself a break ð«¶ð

Lots of people think creativity is something we're born with, and we either have it or need to stay away from it as much as possible cause it's not for us. 

And I think the problem is that society propagates a very narrow definition of what creativity looks like. 

Does this sound like you?

"Oh, my classmate paints so well. She's creative. 
Oh this guy is a writer, must have a creative mind. 
This other girl does clay sculpting, hmm yeah it's cause she's a creative soul. 

But me? Oh no, I'm not creative yaar, cause I don't paint, or write or sing or do clay sculpting and what not." 

ðIf this is you then I'm here to tell you that creativity is not so much about an activity (painting, writing, sculpting, ect) but it's a way of relating to things. 

I'm doing an online workshop this Sunday that already has over 200 participants. If you want to know more about how to nurture your dormant creative side just send me this reel and I'll respond :)
